author: freep.com
title: Michigan Wolverines respectful with eyes focused on Michigan State
text:
MORE After beating down yet another opponent,
Northwestern the latest victim in a 38-0 trouncing
, the fifth straight win in this suddenly stunning season, the Michigan football players were going out on Saturday night.
Either a trip to Buffalo Wild Wings or a cookout at someone's house, they would have their eyes fixed in one direction: on the Michigan State-Rutgers game.
Tailback De'Veon Smith said that's their move regardless of the teams played – they even watched Cincinnati against Memphis one Saturday night – but few were buying that with his grin.
He knows the No. 4 Spartans, who have won five of the past six against the Wolverines, are coming to Ann Arbor next week.
But this U-M team under coach Jim Harbaugh is not the same.
"I believe so," Smith said. "We prepare better, overall we have that confidence and swagger about us. I feel we believe in each other so we think we can win this week."
Watching the Spartans thrive recently, rolling over U-M by a combined 64-17 score the past two years on their way to consecutive top 5 finishes, is the Wolverines' burden.
"Yeah, it's frustrating losing to them but you've got to get over it, you've got to go game by game and can't really think about the past," Smith said.
Speaking before the MSU game on Saturday night, the Wolverines all offered respect to the Spartans but chose their words carefully.
■ Jabrill Peppers: "They're a good team, but we're just trying to enjoy this win and when we come in tomorrow we'll watch the film and start the game plan process."
■ Jourdan Lewis: "We haven't seen film on them yet. They're a good team, they're a great team actually but we'll just enjoy this win."
■ Harbaugh: "Tremendous opponent, going to demand we're at our very best, that's going to mean a great week of preparation and practices in store for us. Move on more quickly than usual because it is such a good worthy opponent next week. And we'll be looking forward to it."
Harbaugh expects his team won't be overwhelmed by the hype or the rivalry.
"Every week's a test, win the next game, it's always a big task," Harbaugh said. "I think they'll do good."
